# FHIR Standards Guide

This project follows HL7 FHIR (Fast Healthcare Interoperability Resources) standards for healthcare data exchange and clinical workflow integration.

## Key Principles

- **Resource-Based**: All clinical data should be represented as FHIR Resources (Patient, Observation, Procedure, Encounter, etc.)
- **RESTful API**: Use FHIR REST API conventions for resource operations (GET, POST, PUT, DELETE)
- **JSON Format**: Prefer JSON serialization for FHIR resources
- **Versioning**: Specify FHIR version (e.g., R4, R5) in API endpoints and resource metadata

## Common Resources for Surgical Monitoring

- **Patient**: Patient demographics and identifiers
- **Encounter**: Hospital visits, surgical procedures
- **Procedure**: Surgical procedures and interventions
- **Observation**: Vital signs, monitoring data, clinical measurements
- **Device**: Medical devices and equipment used during surgery
- **ProcedureRequest/ServiceRequest**: Surgical procedure requests
- **DiagnosticReport**: Lab results, imaging reports
- **MedicationAdministration**: Medications given during surgery

## Best Practices

- Always validate FHIR resources against the FHIR schema before sending/receiving
- Use proper FHIR data types (CodeableConcept, Quantity, DateTime, etc.)
- Include proper metadata (meta, id, versionId) for resource tracking
- Follow FHIR search parameter conventions for querying resources
- Implement proper error handling using FHIR OperationOutcome resources
- Ensure HIPAA compliance when handling PHI (Protected Health Information)

